          <h3>What is The Noneo?</h3>
          <p>
            <strong>The Noneo</strong> is the Korean literal translation of the original Chinese character name of the Analects, which is Lunyu (論語). The Chinese characters are transcribed as such:
          </p>
          <p class="lead">
            English: The Analects of Confucius
          </p>
          <p class="lead">
            Traditional Chinese: 論語 lúnyǔ
          </p>
          <p class="lead">
            Korean: 논어 noneo <small>(pronounced as /noʊn ə/ or 'non-uh')</small>
          </p>
          <p>
            While the most commonly cited English translation of the 論語/논어 is <i>'Edited Conversations'</i>, the 論/논 character can be translated as 'Discuss/Debate' and the 語/어 character translated as 'Conversation'. <a href="#c-9" class="citation" title="Ancient Chinese characters are difficult to translate, because their meanings are more symbollic than semantic. For example, the original character for 'filial piety' (孝) is of the 'son' character (子) written beneath the 'senior' (耂) chracter to signify that the son is literally 'supporting' the senior."><span id="rfn-9"></span>[9]</a><a href="#c-10" class="citation" title="Observant readers will notice that there is a 1 to 1 translation from the Ancient Chinese characters to Korean characters going on here. This is true for most Ancient Chinese characters."><span id="rfn-10"></span>[10]</a>  The actual literal translations are more accurately <i>'Discussed Conversations'</i>. The <i>'Edited Conversations'</i> translation comes from the effort to note the fact that Confucius' disciples edited the conversations they had and compiled it into a literary work, as most modern scholars agree that Confucius is not the author of the Analects in the traditional sense of the word. It is comparable to how Socrates never wrote down any of his ideas either, but he is cited for his philosophies as recorded by his disciple, Plato.
          </p>
          <p>
            For simplicity, 'Noneo' refers to this website and its interpretations and commentary, and the term 'Analects' refers to the original text.
          </p>
